children.title: Plan your business
Market research and competitive analysis
children.summary: Market research helps you find customers for your business. Competitive analysis helps you make your business unique. Combine them to find a competitive advantage for your small business.

children.title: Write your business plan
children.summary: Your business plan is the foundation of your business. Learn how to write a business plan quickly and efficiently with a business plan template.

children.title: Calculate your startup costs
children.summary: How much money will it take to start your small business? Calculate the startup costs for your small business so you can request funding, attract investors, and estimate when you’ll turn a profit.

children.title: Fund your business
children.summary: It costs money to start a business. Funding your business is one of the first — and most important — financial choices most business owners make. How you choose to fund your business could affect how you structure and run your business.

children.title: Buy an existing business or franchise
children.summary: It can be hard to start a business from scratch. Starting a business from scratch can be challenging. The good news? You don’t have to start from scratch to have your own business. Consider franchising or buying an existing business.

children.description: You've got a great idea. Now, make a plan to turn it into a great business.

children.title: Launch your business
Pick your business location
children.summary: Your business location determines the taxes, zoning laws, and regulations your business will be subject to. You'll need to make a strategic decision about which state, city, and neighborhood you choose to start your business in.

children.title: Choose a business structure
children.summary: The business structure you choose influences everything from day-to-day operations, to taxes, to how much of your personal assets are at risk. You should choose a business structure that gives you the right balance of legal protections and benefits.

children.title: Choose your business name
children.summary: You can find the right business name with creativity and market research. Once you’ve picked your name, you should protect it by registering it with the right agencies.

children.title: Register your business
children.summary: Register your business to make it a distinct legal entity. How and where you need to register depends on your business structure and business location.

children.title: Get federal and state tax ID numbers
children.summary: Your state tax ID and federal tax ID numbers — also known as an Employer Identification Number (EIN) —  work like a personal social security number, but for your business. They let your small business pay state and federal taxes.

children.title: Apply for licenses and permits
children.summary: Most small businesses need a combination of licenses and permits from both federal and state agencies. The requirements — and fees — vary based on your business activities, location, and government rules.

children.title: Open a business bank account
children.summary: Open a business account when you're ready to start accepting or spending money as your business. A business bank account helps you stay legally compliant and protected. It also provides benefits to your customers and employees.

children.title: Get business insurance
children.summary: Business insurance protects you from the unexpected costs of running a business. Accidents, natural disasters, and lawsuits could run you out of business if you’re not protected with the right insurance.

children.description: Turn your business into a reality. Register, file, and start doing business.

children.title: Manage your business
Manage your finances
children.summary: Accounting for revenue and expenses can help keep your business running smoothly. Make sure you maintain proper bookkeeping and have a basic knowledge of business finances.

children.title: Hire and manage employees
children.summary: Establish a basic payroll structure to help you hire employees. Then, manage employees properly with a general understanding of state and federal labor laws.

children.title: Pay taxes
children.summary: Your business will need to meet its federal, state, and local tax obligations to stay in good legal standing. Your business structure and location will influence which taxes your business has to pay.

children.title: Stay legally compliant
children.summary: Keep your business compliant with state and federal business laws. Your legal responsibilities will depend on your business and location.

children.title: Buy assets and equipment
children.summary: Your business will need special assets and equipment to succeed. Figure out which assets you need, how to pay for them, and whether you should buy government surplus.

children.title: Marketing and sales
children.summary: Make a marketing plan to persuade consumers to buy your products or services, then decide how you’ll accept payment when it’s time to make a sale.

children.title: Prepare for emergencies
children.summary: Smart planning can help you keep your business running if disaster strikes. You’ll want to take the right steps to prevent and prepare for disaster, and know where to get aid if disaster strikes.

children.title: Close or sell your business
children.summary: Create a thorough plan to transfer ownership, sell, or close your business. Get qualified advice and know what to do to tie up loose ends.

children.description: Run your business like a boss. Master day-to-day operations and prepare for success.

children.title: Grow your business
Get more funding
children.summary: If your business is up and running but needs more capital, you can rely on familiar options. However, funding an existing business still requires slightly different preparation.

children.title: Expand to new locations
children.summary: Once you’re ready to expand, update the marketing plan and confirm that your business is financially prepared. Then, make sure to comply with all laws, rules, and regulations in the new business locations.

children.title: Merge and acquire businesses
children.summary: You can grow your business by buying or merging with a smaller business. The process is similar to starting a new business, but you need to take extra steps to protect your existing business.

children.title: Become a federal contractor
children.summary: The federal government encourages small businesses to take on contracting opportunities. The process to register as a federal contractor is more straight-forward than most people think.

children.title: Export products
children.summary: Export goods to increase your profits, reduce market dependence, and stabilize seasonal sales. Connect with Small Business Administration resources and partners to get help exporting.

children.title: Women-owned businesses
children.summary: The SBA helps women entrepreneurs launch new businesses and compete in the marketplace. Connect with the training and funding opportunities specifically for women.

children.title: Native American-owned businesses
children.summary: The federal government provides opportunities in contracting, business development, and other programs for Native American small business owners.

children.title: Veteran-owned businesses
children.summary: The SBA offers support for veterans as they enter the world of business ownership. Look for funding programs, training, and federal contracting opportunities.

children.description: When business is good, it's time to expand. Find new funding, locations, and customers.

children.title: Loans
children.description: Start or expand your business with loans guaranteed by the Small Business Administration.
children.summary: Start or expand your business with loans guaranteed by the Small Business Administration. Use Lender Match to find lenders that offer loans for your business.

children.title: Investment capital
children.description: Find an investor for your business. Investors make both debt and equity investments.
children.summary: Find an investor for your business through a Small Business Investment Company (SBIC) licensed by the Small Business Administration (SBA).

children.title: Disaster assistance
children.description: Get help after a disaster with low-interest disaster loans from the Small Business Administration.
children.summary: The SBA provides low-interest disaster loans to help small businesses and homeowners recover from declared disasters.

children.title: Surety bonds
children.description: Protect your work and your client with an SBA-guaranteed surety bond.
children.summary: The Small Business Administration (SBA) guarantees bid, performance, and payment surety bonds issued by certain surety companies.

children.title: Grants
children.description: Look for government grants that help businesses do scientific research and development.
children.summary: The SBA doesn’t give grants to start or expand a business. Small businesses and nonprofits conducting research and development can apply for grants at SBIR.gov.

children.title: Lenders
7(a) loan program
Operate as a 7(a) lender
children.summary: The Small Business Administration (SBA) has streamlined the lending process for its lenders. Review the major activities you regularly perform as a lender in the 7(a) program and the SBA tools you use.

children.title: Types of 7(a) loans
children.summary: The 7(a) loan program is the Small Business Administration’s (SBA) primary program for providing financial assistance to small businesses. The terms and conditions, like the guaranty percentage and loan amount, may vary by the type of loan.

children.title: Pilot loan programs
children.summary: SBA lenders can participate in two pilot loan programs, Community Advantage and Express Bridge. These pilot programs will operate for a limited time, unless extended or made a permanent part of the SBA’s loan programs.

children.title: Secondary market
children.summary: There’s an active secondary market for loans backed by the Small Business Administration (SBA). As a lender, you can sell the guaranteed portion of an SBA loan, increasing your liquidity and enabling you to issue more loans.

children.title: Terms, conditions, and eligibility
children.summary: The Small Business Administration (SBA) sets the guidelines that govern the 7(a) loan program. As a lender, these conditions determine which businesses you can lend to and the type of loans you can give.
If you’re a member of a financial institution authorized by the SBA to issue 7(a) loans, use this page to access SBA forms, get program updates, and more.

children.title: CDC/504 loan program
Operate as a CDC
children.summary: The Small Business Administration (SBA) has streamlined the lending process for CDCs. Review the major activities you regularly perform in the CDC/504 program and the SBA tools you use.

children.title: List of CDCs
children.summary: The SBA works with CDCs across the country.

children.title: Secondary market
children.summary: There’s an active secondary market for CDC debentures that are backed by the Small Business Administration (SBA). As a CDC, you can sell these guaranteed debentures to investors.
If your organization is designated by the SBA as a CDC authorized to issue 504 loans, use this page to access SBA forms, get program updates, and more.

children.title: Microloan program
Operate as an intermediary
children.summary: The SBA gives intermediaries the authority to issue Microloans. These loans have certain conditions between the SBA and intermediaries, and certain conditions between intermediaries and borrowers.

children.title: List of lenders
children.summary: The SBA works with designated intermediary lenders across the country to provide financing to small businesses. Find an intermediary near you.
If your organization is designated by the SBA as an intermediary in its Microloan program, use this page to access SBA forms, get program updates, and more.

children.title: Become an SBA lender
children.summary: As an SBA-certified lender, small business loans you issue will be backed by a federal guaranty.

children.description: Partner with the Small Business Administration to issue government-guaranteed loans.
children.summary: Financial institutions and other organizations work with the SBA to give small businesses loans. The SBA has three loan programs: 7(a), CDC/504, and Microloans.

children.title: SBICs
children.description: Get access to low-cost, government-backed capital to invest in small businesses.

children.title: Surety bond partners and agents
Operate as a surety bond partner or agent
children.summary: The SBA has made it easier for surety agents to quickly issue government-backed surety bonds. This new process saves time and paperwork.

children.title: List of surety bond partners
children.summary: The SBA works with surety bond companies across the country. Find a surety company near you.

children.title: Become an SBA surety partner
children.summary: Are you a surety bond company or licensed surety agent? Do you underwrite contract surety bonds? If so, the SBA may be a valuable partner to you.

children.description: Issue surety bonds secured by a guarantee from the Small Business Administration.
children.summary: If you’re a surety partner or agent participating in the SBA's Surety Bond Guarantee program, use this page to access SBA forms, get program updates, and more.

title: Disaster assistance

children.title: Hurricane Harvey
children.summary: Find SBA disaster loans and business counseling for people and businesses affected by Hurricane Harvey.

children.title: Hurricane Irma
children.summary: Find SBA disaster loans and business counseling for people and businesses affected by Hurricane Irma.

children.title: Hurricane Maria
children.summary: Find SBA disaster loans and business counseling for people and businesses affected by Hurricane Maria.

children.title: Hurricane response jobs at the SBA
children.summary: The Small Business Administration is not currently hiring for disaster relief jobs.  When positions are again needed, we will post listings here.

children.title: Disaster response contracts
children.summary: When national emergencies or natural disasters occur, supplies and services need to be rushed to affected areas quickly. Small businesses can contract with the federal government to assist in relief and recovery efforts following a major disaster.

summary: The SBA provides low-interest disaster loans to help small businesses and homeowners recover from declared disasters.

title: Home page
summary: We support America's small businesses. The SBA connects entrepreneurs with lenders and funding to help them plan, start and grow their business.
